AB  - We examine how research and development (R&amp;D) incoming spillovers affect long-run firm performance following firms’ R&amp;D increases. We use a stochastic frontier production method to capture R&amp;D incoming spillover effects. Firms reaping more benefits from R&amp;D investment made by other firms experience more improvement in profitability and more favorable long-run stock performance in the post-R&amp;D-increase period. Firms with higher levels of R&amp;D incoming spillovers recruit more key employees from other firms, suggesting that obtaining know-how through hiring is an important source of incoming spillovers. The evidence also shows that firms experiencing more R&amp;D outgoing spillover effects tend to underinvest in R&amp;D.
